In a #small pot{}, combine @Jasmine Rice{3/4%cup}, @water{1 1/4%cups} and a pinhc of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook, covered, until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Wash and dry produce. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @Yellow Onion{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @Apricot Jam{2%tbsp}, @Sweet Thai Chili Sauce{2%oz}, half the @Soy Sauce{2%tbsp}, and @hot water{3%tbsp}. Set apricot-chili duck sauce aside.

> 5 TBSP hot water for 4 servings.

In a #large pan{}, heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{2%tsp} over medium-high heat. Add @pork{10%oz}, @Garlic Powder{1%tsp}, and a pinch of @Salt{pinch} and @Pepper{pinch}. Using a #spatula{}, press into an even layer. Cook, without stirring, until browned on bottom, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Break up meat into pieces and continue cooking until pork is cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add half the apricot-chili duck sauce; cook, stirring occasionally, until pork is glazed and coated, ~{1-3%minutes}. Turn off heat. Transfer pork to a #plate{}; tent with #foil{} until ready to serve. Wipe out pan.

> Rinse shrimp under cold water; pat dry with paper towels. Swap in shrimp or beef for pork; cook through this step as instructed (no need to break up shrimp into pieces!).

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{2%tsp} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add @Coleslaw Mix{4%oz}, @Shredded Carrots{4%oz}, and @Yellow Onion{1}(thinly sliced); cook, stirring occasionally, until tender and browned, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add @Sesame Oil{1%tbsp} and remaining soy sauce. Cook, stirring, until flavors meld, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

Fluff rice with a #fork{} and stir in @Butter{1%tbsp}. Season with salt and pepper. Divide rice between bowls; top with pork, veggies, and @Crispy Fried Onions{1}. Drizzle with remaining apricot-chili duck sauce. Serve.

> Shrimp is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.